I’m so ready to taste these black strawberry tomatoes! I grew them from my @bakercreekseeds tomatoes haul back in January. The spoon tomatoes came from there as well. Hurry up and ripen already!

In other news, if you listened to the audio on this reel, Nugget, my head hen extraordinaire, the Queen of the Coop, passed away suddenly from unknown causes on Sunday. She was 16 months old. I’de been out with them, refreshing waters, and giving some good Sunday snuggles earlier, and now I’m so glad I’d held her so much, because 90 minutes later the Lion noticed she was dead. 

The Chicken Palace isn’t the same without our bossy Chicken Nugget. Her hatchmates, Chick Norris and Henny Penny seem lost without her. The power vacuum has led to a bit of anarchy, and momentarily everyone switched coops except for poor Rose, who’s as confused as ever. Me, being open to exploiting all chaos in the Chicken Realm, decided now was the time to merge the two coops to give everyone a better chance of surviving the fast-approaching winter. Too few Big Girls remain to keep the big coop warm, and the little coop is too drafty for the 5 Little Girls to do well, even though it’s only built for 3 tops and is way over crowded. In all the confusion on Sunday, they also managed to rip their roosting bar clean off the wall, so there’s that.

Stay tuned for more Chicken Realm shenanigans, and let me know what’s ripening in your garden this week!

Now that fall is here, it’s time to pick my sourdough back up. When the temps got up there in August, my sourdough started peaking in 3-4 hours - way too early for me to keep up with it and still do all the things! So I parked it, to be picked up later.

That’s one of the hardest things about life (at least for me!), recognizing when the season for something is over for now, and it’s time to hit pause. Not stop, just pause, to be picked up again later.

For everything there is a season, and a time for every matter under heaven. ~ Ecclesiastes 3:1

I’ve had a couple questions about keeping my sourdough warm enough to rise and peak in a cold house now that temps are dropping. Keep in mind, our house is wood stove heated with electric baseboard backup. This actually works to my advantage because I’m able to run only the heater in the living room/homeschool room to take the chill off in the morning, and let the rest of the house stay cool from overnight. 

Option 1 - in the oven with just the light on. I use this on colder days. Days like today, when it’s 63° outside, and 68° in the kitchen, I use 

Option 2 - in the warm nook between the heater and the couch. It’s not cold enough for a fire, so I just turn one heater on, set to 68° so it only turns on if it drops below that. That little corner feels slightly warmer, so it helps my sourdough starter stay nice and comfy. This is also my favorite proofing spot when I’m backing bread. 

Do you keep your sourdough in the kitchen, or does it travel around like mine?

#sourdough #sourdoughstarter #glutenfreesourdough #glutenfreesourdoughstarter #homemadebread #homebakedbread

We’ve been super busy over here with birthday parties for June Bugs and preparing for single digit temps while 3 of our 6 ladies molt. It’s been 2 days since we last got an egg. Please send sunshine!

We also lost Tulip on Friday. The details are too terrible to share on here, but suffice it to say I was pretty upset. I was finally able to burry her properly today. For those playing along at home, she was the little Cuckoo Marans poult that “helped” me earn my Crazy Chicken Lady Obstetrics badge last spring. Her gentle coo and sweet disposition is missed in our tiny backyard flock.

As God generally does, he sent me a little gift of this beautiful Zinnia feather nestled perfectly in the nesting box  the next day. He sees us, and draws especially near when we’re sad.

TO GOD BE THE GLORY!

It’s finally baking time! Now that I’m finally past the plague, I’m playing catch-up in the kitchen. My real-life friend, @joyfulmomma just released a Christmas Cookie cookbook, and I’m aiming to bake my way through it between now and Sunday, but subbing gf ingredients to make them celiac friendly. The peanut butter blossoms are not from the cookbook, but if I don’t make them, this pirate ship will have mutiny!

Once those were out of the way I moved on to cookie 1 - Soft Ginger Sandwich Cookies. My dear, dear friends, I’ve never worked with such a light and fluffy cookie dough before! These are amazing! I’ll be whipping up the cream cheese filling and assembling tomorrow as well as moving on to cookies 2 and 3. 

This is going to be ambitious for me while I’m still nursing sick kiddos, but I’m going to try to make all 12 cookies, even if it takes me well into next week. They can be New Years cookies, right?

#christmascookies #12daysofchristmascookies #christmasbaking #holidaybaking #glutenfreebaking #glutenfreechristmas #homesteadkitchen

First polar vortex of the year. Yay. 

The girls had zero interest in going outside for food and water, and their heated waterer froze solid last night, so today I’ve done the following:

- Every 3 hours, run a bowl of water out to the hen house. Retrieve 10 minutes later. This allows them to drink without it freezing or creating condensation inside the coop. 
- Free feeding of both layer crumbles and high protein scratch grains. Their usual feeder froze to the ground, so I’m using my biggest food storage bowls. Gotta do whatcha gotta do!

I’ve got a more tropical breed, Iniga, that I’m keeping a close eye on, and a crested, Rose, and a larger combed lady, Pepper, that I’m also keeping a close eye on, but so far, so good! Three more days of this and we’ll be through it!

How’s the polar vortex treating you?
